For some reason Cato included the first three years of the Second Punic War, with the battle of Cannae, in the fourth book.2 The fifth book completed the Second Punic War, with subsequent events as far as the final conquest of Macedonia. It also contained at least one of Cato's own orations, inserted at its proper place in the narrative.3 The last two books, the sixth and seventh, continued the story with greater detail, and a more liberal sprinkling, in all probability, of Cato’s speeches,⁴ to the year of his death, 149. From the First Punic War on, we are told that he omitted the names of the com- manders.⁵ He found space, however, to mention places and objects of interest in Italy and Spain.
